Rating: 1
This recipe sounded very likable and I wanted to like it. However I didn't and neither did my family. I made it exactly as written. It wasn't terrible, just not very good. Baked turkey tenderloins get a little rubbery (cooked them to exacly 160) and turkey and pesto don't do anything for each other. The flavors don't work together and end up tasting like somewhat bland turkey with well..pesto on it. Despite closing them tightly and putting the cut side up, all the cheese melts out and ends up in the pan, which is the best part - melted crispy cheese with pesto in it. It looks beautiful though.

Rating: 2
Wish I could give it 2.5 forks! This was very good, a perfect mid-week meal as it took less than 15 minutes to make. The paired flavors of the pesto and provolone were very tasty. Even though I secured the breasts with toothpicks, the cheese still managed to ooze out of the chicken. No matter, though, as it pooled around the chicken breast and browned in a lacy pattern, and I was able to lift the cheese and the breast together with a spatula. It looked like I had done it on purpose, tasted great and was quite pretty. I also topped the breasts w/ a half slice of cheese in the last 5 minutes. This will definitely go into the rotation!

Rating: 4
Fabulous make ahead dish! I like to add sun dried tomato or roasted red pepper for added zing and color. serve it with spinach topped tomatoes, beautiful combination.

Rating: 4
This recipe was very easy to make! While this is cooking, I kept opening the oven and spooning the oil back on to the meat. It's full of flavor and if you get the right kind of pesto, you don't need to do much in seasonings. One suggestion I have is that it should probably stay in the oven for more than 20 minutes.

Rating: 3
This is really, really good. I was skeptical because I wasn't wild about the pesto that I had, but the combination with the cheese was perfect. This is really rich and I find I can't eat it too often, once every couple of months.

